Now let me understand the current test to see the pattern `DeepCloneRecordShouldNotUseCtorMapping`. The test at line 64 says records should NOT use ctor mapping in deep cloning. But the bug report says that when `[MapperConstructor]` is present, it should override this behavior.

Let me now look deeper into the `CtorMappingBuilder.TryBuildMapping` method. The key issue is: it finds a single-arg constructor where the parameter matches the source type. In deep cloning mode, the source and target are the same type, so any copy constructor matches. But it should check if `[MapperConstructor]` is present on a different constructor.

Let me also check if there's already any `[MapperConstructor]` awareness in `CtorMappingBuilder`:

Looking at the code again (lines 31-54), I see that `FindSingleArgCtor` simply finds the first accessible constructor with 1 parameter matching the source type. It doesn't check for `[MapperConstructor]`.

The fix should be in `CtorMappingBuilder.TryBuildMapping`: when `UseDeepCloning` is enabled and the source/target types are the same, we should skip the copy constructor selection if `[MapperConstructor]` is present on any other constructor. Let me also check if there's behavior when `MapperConstructor` is on the copy constructor itself.

Let me look at the `NewInstanceObjectMemberMappingBodyBuilder.BuildConstructorMapping` more carefully (we already read it). Lines 49-54 show:

```csharp
// attributed ctor is prio 1
// if preferParameterlessConstructors is true (default) :parameterless ctor is prio 2 then by descending parameter count
// the reverse if preferParameterlessConstructors is false , descending parameter count is prio2 then parameterless ctor
// ctors annotated with [Obsolete] are considered last unless they have a MapperConstructor attribute set
var ctorCandidates = namedTargetType
    .InstanceConstructors.Where(ctor => ctx.BuilderContext.SymbolAccessor.IsConstructorAccessible(ctor))
    .OrderByDescending(x => ctx.BuilderContext.SymbolAccessor.HasAttribute<MapperConstructorAttribute>(x))
    .ThenBy(x => ctx.BuilderContext.SymbolAccessor.HasAttribute<ObsoleteAttribute>(x));
```

So `NewInstanceObjectMemberMappingBodyBuilder` already handles `[MapperConstructor]`. The problem is that the `CtorMappingBuilder.TryBuildMapping` runs BEFORE `NewInstanceObjectMemberMappingBuilder.TryBuildMapping` and if it finds a matching copy constructor, it short-circuits and the member mapping builder never gets to apply `[MapperConstructor]`.

The fix should be in `CtorMappingBuilder.TryBuildMapping`. When `UseDeepCloning` is enabled and the source type is the same as the target type, we need to check if there's a `[MapperConstructor]` on any constructor. If there is, we should skip the copy constructor selection, allowing the `NewInstanceObjectMemberMappingBodyBuilder` to handle the `[MapperConstructor]` properly.

Wait, let me re-read the builder chain. In `MappingBuilder.cs`:
- Line 27: `CtorMappingBuilder.TryBuildMapping` - picks copy ctor 
- Line 35: `NewInstanceObjectMemberMappingBuilder.TryBuildMapping` - never reached if CtorMapping succeeds

So the fix is: in `CtorMappingBuilder.TryBuildMapping`, when we find a single-arg constructor that takes the same type as the source (i.e., a copy constructor), check if there's also a `[MapperConstructor]` attribute on any other constructor. If so, return null to let `NewInstanceObjectMemberMappingBuilder` handle it.

Actually wait, let me think more carefully. Looking at the test `DeepCloneRecordShouldNotUseCtorMapping`:

```csharp
var source = TestSourceBuilder.Mapping(
    "A",
    "A",
    TestSourceBuilderOptions.WithDeepCloning,
    "record A { public int Value { get; set; } }"
);
```

This maps `A` to `A` and expects it to NOT use the ctor mapping but instead creates a new object with `new global::A()`. This is because a record has a synthesized copy ctor but we don't want to use it for deep cloning.

But the user wants: when `[MapperConstructor]` is on a parameterless constructor, that should take priority over the copy ctor. The current behavior ignores `[MapperConstructor]` entirely when a copy ctor exists.

Let me check: is there a way the CtorMappingBuilder knows if deep cloning is in effect? Looking at `CtorMappingBuilder.TryBuildMapping`:

```csharp
public static CtorMapping? TryBuildMapping(MappingBuilderContext ctx)
{
    if (!ctx.IsConversionEnabled(MappingConversionType.Constructor))
        return null;

    if (ctx.Target is not INamedTypeSymbol namedTarget)
        return null;

    // resolve ctors which have the source as single argument
    var ctor = FindSingleArgCtor(namedTarget, ctx.Source, ctx.SymbolAccessor);
    if (ctor == null)
        return null;

    return new CtorMapping(ctx.Source, ctx.Target, ctx.InstanceConstructors.BuildForConstructor(ctor));
}
```

It uses `MappingConversionType.Constructor`. Let me check what the default conversion types include:

